    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4e7ddd1d-aabc-44ee-b3be-41295c25375a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an 8-year-old boy who appears tired but alert, sitting close to his mother and speaking in a softer voice than usual because of throat pain. He is mildly flushed, intermittently swallows with discomfort, and occasionally winces when trying to eat or drink. Over the last 2 days he has had a sore throat, painful swallowing, low-grade fever, reduced appetite, and mild fatigue. He denies shortness of breath, drooling, or neck stiffness. He has a small build for his age but is generally healthy and well cared for.\n\n{patientName} is a second-grade student who enjoys playing soccer at recess, collecting toy cars, and building with blocks at home. He lives with his parents and an older sister in a suburban apartment, and the family keeps a regular routine with school, homework, and weekend visits to his grandparents. Several classmates have recently had upper respiratory illnesses, and his mother reports that he developed symptoms shortly after a child in his class was sent home sick.\n\nAt home, {patientName} usually has a good energy level and sleeps well, though the sore throat has caused restless sleep for the past night. He is drinking less than usual because swallowing hurts, but he is still taking small sips of water and juice. His parents are attentive and brought him in because he has become less interested in meals and complained repeatedly that his throat \"burns\" when he swallows.\n\nHis family describes him as friendly, active, and generally resilient, with no developmental concerns. He has no tobacco exposure in the home, no recent travel, and no known sick contacts outside of school. The household is supportive, and his mother has been giving him fluids, cool foods, and rest while monitoring for worsening fever or breathing difficulty."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:85cdb104-50d7-47cd-81d8-894387d39fb0",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no significant chronic medical conditions and has had normal growth and development. He has never been hospitalized and has no history of recurrent tonsillitis, asthma, congenital heart disease, or immunodeficiency. His immunizations are up to date for age. He occasionally gets common colds during the school year but otherwise has been in good health.\n\nHe was born at term without perinatal complications and has no history of major surgeries. His parents report no recent antibiotic use and no prior serious medication reactions. He is generally active, participates in school sports, and eats a typical mixed diet, though he can be selective with vegetables. He drinks water and milk regularly and rarely consumes caffeinated or sugary beverages.\n\nThere is no smoke exposure at home. He attends primary school, where there have been recent sick contacts with upper respiratory symptoms. His current illness began acutely with sore throat and fever, and his parents brought him for evaluation because of pain with swallowing and decreased appetite. There is no history of choking, foreign body ingestion, muffled voice, drooling, trismus, or respiratory distress."
          }
        ]
      }
